Orchestrates the count-expansion and type-append pipeline (Pass A + Pass B) plus the one-liner line-flag pass, turning a parsed `Entry` AST into the `TypedEntry` records that both renderers (steno's translation and doc renderers, per the module doc) consume. This is the top-level module for `crate::expand`; it re-exports the public surface of six submodules (`append`, `counts`, `family`, `lineflag`, `types`) and keeps `fill` private — `fill` has no `pub use`, so it's only reachable through the other submodules' internals, not from outside this module.

Defines the two staging structs: `ExpandedEntry` (Pass A output — count-resolved `template: Vec<Chunk>` with no `repeat`/`dcount`/`computed` chunks left, plus the resolved `count` and original `source: Entry`) and `TypedEntry` (Pass B output — every type slot resolved, plus `terminal: bool` and `one_liner: bool` flags that downstream renderers branch on: non-terminal entries skip bracing/movement, and `one_liner` entries collapse every `%b` instead of breaking).

`expand_dict(entries: &[Entry], generic_arg_strokes: Option<&[&str]>) -> Result<Vec<TypedEntry>, ExpandError>` is the single entry point tying everything together, and its internal order is load-bearing: it first calls `build_type_set` to separate `@type`-flagged entries into the `types`/`arity0` pools, then — if `generic_arg_strokes` is `Some` — filters `arity0` down to only strokes present in that slice (silently drops any that don't match); entries flagged `is_type()` are excluded from further processing (they're consumed as type definitions, never emitted themselves). For each remaining entry it runs `expand_counts` (Pass A, can multiply one entry into several via count expansion) then `expand_types_one` per expansion (Pass B). Only after all entries are typed does it call `fix_family_terminals` (mutates terminal flags across the whole `Vec<TypedEntry>` — must see the complete set to work correctly) and finally `expand_line_flag`, which does its own pass over the full typed vector and can itself fail (returns the outer `Result`). Reordering these steps (e.g., running family/line-flag per-entry instead of over the whole vec) will break entries whose terminal/line-flag status depends on sibling entries.